<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-720-277  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 720 277.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  Dec 24, 1990 v5 n126 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>International: ATandamp;T andamp; NTT start first phase of new, high-speedoptical communications system. (Nippon Telegraph and TelephoneCorp.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Network Systems (Contracts)Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsInternational CommunicationsNetworksContractsCooperative AgreementProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation (NTT) Tuesday placed into servicethe first phase of a new, high-speed optical communications systemmanufactured by ATandamp;T Network Systems at North Andover, Massachusetts.andM;The equipment is part of a $154 million contract awarded to ATandamp;T NetworkSystems in July, 1989.andP;  This contract represented the first major purchase ofU.S.andP;  made optical communications equipment by a Japanese company.andM;The new system was developed by ATandamp;T Bell Laboratories and was manufacturedat ATandamp;T's Merrimack Valley Works.andP;  The system is designed to sendhigh-capacity lightwave signals up to 80 kilometers (about 50 miles) withoutregeneration.andP;  The system transmits information at the rate of 622 millionbits per second, which is equivalent to 8,000 simultaneous telephone calls.andM;ATandamp;T developed the new system and equipment to meet NTT requirements and itshigh standards for quality and reliability.andP;  NTT is using the equipment inits long distance telephone network to provide intelligent network servicesto its customers.andM;The system conforms to the evolving Synchronous Optical Network/SynchronousDigital Hierarchy (SONET/SDH) communications standard.andP;  SONET/SDH defines ahierarchy of optical transmission rates and formats to be used worldwide bymanufacturers, carriers and end users.andM;A SONET/SDH signal is made up of two components, one carrying system trafficand another carrying administration and network management data through thenetwork.andM;Communications equipment built to these standards will help carriersaccommodate growth in their networks, respond more rapidly to their users'needs, improve operations and maintenance, and introduce more quicklysophisticated new services.andP;  The SONET/SDH standard will also allow equipmentfrom different manufacturers to communicate, making it easier to designnetworks.andO;</TEXT></DOC>